---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  pageHeading="West Side Infrastructure"
  description="The obvious gap in KC mesh coverage: west side. Here's what a west-side deployment would look like if you wanted to do it."
>
  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">
      The obvious gap: West side infrastructure
    </h2>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      Router 1 covers the east side—5 to 8 miles from my roof. That's decent coverage east of downtown, Raytown direction, Blue Springs area.
    </p>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      But Johnson County, Overland Park, Lenexa, Shawnee, western KC proper—basically everything west of State Line Road—that's wide open. If someone deployed a router west of State Line with some elevation, they'd bridge the gap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Why This Matters -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-red/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-red/5 to-sunset-amber/5 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-sunset-amber/20 dark:from-kc-red/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-kc-red dark:text-sunset-amber">Why west side is the logical next piece</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Two routers create functional backbone coverage.</strong> East router + west router gives you cross-metro coverage. Client nodes fill in density between them, and you've got usable infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        North and south routers eventually complete the cardinal coverage. But the west side deployment is what makes the network actually work for most of the KC metro population.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>That's the obvious next step for anyone looking to deploy infrastructure.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Current Coverage Gap -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What's currently not covered</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Here are areas that would benefit immediately from a west-side router:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Johnson County areas</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Overland Park</li>
          <li>• Leawood</li>
          <li>• Shawnee</li>
          <li>• Lenexa</li>
          <li>• Olathe (western portions)</li>
          <li>• Prairie Village</li>
          <li>• Mission / Roeland Park area</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">KC Metro west side</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Westport area</li>
          <li>• Plaza / Brookside</li>
          <li>• Waldo</li>
          <li>• Ward Parkway corridor</li>
          <li>• Western KC city limits</li>
          <li>• North Kansas City (western portions)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-kc-blue/5 border border-kc-blue/20 p-5 dark:bg-kc-sky/5 dark:border-kc-sky/20">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>That's a lot of people.</strong> Johnson County alone has 600,000+ residents. Router 2 opens mesh networking to a huge portion of the KC metro that currently has zero access to the network.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ideal Site Characteristics -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What you'd need for a west-side deployment</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        A west-side router needs elevation and line-of-sight. Here's what would make a deployment work:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Location (critical)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Target area:</strong> Anywhere in Johnson County or western KC proper west of State Line Road</p>
          <p><strong>Sweet spots:</strong> Overland Park, Shawnee, Lenexa, western KC between I-35 and State Line</p>
          <p><strong>Why:</strong> You'd be bridging the gap between east side coverage and western metro areas</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Elevation (very important)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Minimum:</strong> 15-20 feet above surrounding terrain</p>
          <p><strong>Better:</strong> 30-50 feet (residential tower, tall building, hilltop)</p>
          <p><strong>Ideal:</strong> Repeater site 50-100+ feet (closes coverage gap completely)</p>
          <p><strong>Why:</strong> Height determines range. More height = better metro coverage.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Power (required)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Option 1:</strong> Solar panel mounting space (10-20W panel, ~12"x8" size) - completely independent</p>
          <p><strong>Option 2:</strong> AC power access (weatherproof power supply) - simpler but needs outdoor outlet</p>
          <p><strong>Power draw:</strong> Tiny. About 2-3 watt-hours per day. Less than a nightlight.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Mounting space (required)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Equipment footprint:</strong> Small weatherproof box (~6"x4"x3") plus antenna (12-24" tall)</p>
          <p><strong>Mounting options:</strong> Tower, rooftop, mast, flagpole, fence post, anywhere with height and clear view</p>
          <p><strong>Installation:</strong> DIY-friendly or hire local help. Same setup as Router 1.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Maintenance (minimal)</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>For installation:</strong> One-time setup (1-3 hours for mounting and config)</p>
          <p><strong>For maintenance:</strong> Maybe once or twice a year to check hardware, update firmware</p>
          <p><strong>Remote monitoring:</strong> Check status via mesh network or MQTT without site visits most of the time</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Equipment & Costs -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-blue/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue/5 to-kc-sky/10 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-kc-sky/20 dark:from-kc-blue/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What you'd buy for this deployment</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Equipment costs: ~$150-200 for complete solar setup.</strong> Same hardware as Router 1. Here's the breakdown:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">Core Equipment (~$60-80)</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Meshtastic device (LILYGO T-Echo, Heltec, RAK WisBlock)</li>
          <li>• 915 MHz antenna (5.8 dBi or higher)</li>
          <li>• Weatherproof enclosure</li>
          <li>• Mounting hardware</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">Solar Power (~$90-120)</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• 10-20W solar panel</li>
          <li>• 18650 battery bank (3-4 cells)</li>
          <li>• Solar charge controller</li>
          <li>• Weatherproof power wiring</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-mesh-green/10 border border-mesh-green/30 p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>Alternative:</strong> Skip solar, use AC power. Drops cost to ~$80-100 total. Trade-off: needs outdoor outlet, not grid-independent.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Site Types -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Site types that would work for west-side deployment</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Different site types work for different situations. Here's what would make each one viable:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Amateur radio repeater site</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Why it's ideal:</strong> Tower already exists, elevation is there, you already understand radio infrastructure.</p>
          <p><strong>What you'd need:</strong> Tower space for small enclosure + antenna, mount a tiny solar panel or tap AC power.</p>
          <p><strong>No interference:</strong> Meshtastic is 915 MHz ISM band. Ham repeater is VHF/UHF. Completely separate.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Tall residential property (hill, multi-story)</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Residential rooftop with good elevation provides excellent coverage. Router 1 proves this.</p>
          <p><strong>What you'd need:</strong> Roof or flagpole mounting space. Same setup as Router 1 on the east side.</p>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> House on a hill in Overland Park with 15-foot flagpole. That's plenty.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Commercial building rooftop</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Commercial buildings often have excellent height and roof access already in place.</p>
          <p><strong>What you'd need:</strong> Owner permission, roof mounting space, power access or go solar.</p>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> 3-4 story building in Shawnee or Lenexa gets you great coverage from rooftop.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Church or community building</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Often have height, central locations, mission alignment with emergency comms capability.</p>
          <p><strong>What you'd need:</strong> Board/leadership approval, mounting location (steeple, rooftop, tower).</p>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> Church with steeple in western Johnson County gives excellent elevation.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Water tower or utility structure</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Maximum height, often strategically located for coverage.</p>
          <p><strong>What you'd need:</strong> Municipality or utility company permission (harder to get, but worth trying).</p>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> Water tower in Shawnee or Overland Park. Talk to city infrastructure folks.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Deploy Your Own -->
  <section class="mt-12 text-center">
    <div class="inline-block rounded-3xl bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue to-kc-red p-8 text-cream-50 shadow-card md:p-10">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Ready to deploy your own west-side router?</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-xl text-base opacity-95">
        You've got elevation west of State Line? Deploy your own router. Same setup as Router 1. ~$150-200 hardware, weekend project, fills the obvious gap.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/community/contact"
        class="mt-6 inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-cream-50 px-8 py-3 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-kc-blue transition hover:bg-surface-200"
      >
        Questions? Let's talk →
      </a>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm opacity-75">
        Or coordinate with kansascitymesh.net operator if you want to align on network config. Either way works.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why This Matters (Closing) -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What happens when a west-side router goes live</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>East router + west router = functional backbone coverage across KC metro.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        Client nodes in between can hop between the two routers. People in Johnson County reach people on the east side. You go from "interesting experiment with limited coverage" to "actual useful infrastructure."
      </p>
      <p>
        North and south routers eventually complete the full metro coverage. But the west side deployment is what makes the network actually work for the majority of the KC population.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>That's why west side is the obvious next step. If you've got elevation west of State Line, you can make it happen.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
